üåê Voluntary Adoption and Transitional Governance
This governance model is not intended for global imposition, nor for export as a universal template. Every nation has its own history, culture, and internal logic, and any new system must respect that. The framework is therefore offered as a voluntary option‚Äîa conceptual architecture that each country may investigate, adapt, and implement according to its own needs, values, and developmental path.
The core, non negotiable principle is that the people themselves must make the choice. Any transition toward this model must be initiated by the population, not by existing political elites. To ensure legitimacy and prevent conflicts of interest, the current government and leadership must step aside from the decision making process. They may continue performing routine administrative duties, but they may not influence the design of the new system or position themselves to benefit from it.
To guide the transition, a neutral Interim Governance Process must be established. This interim body has a single mandate:
‚Ä¢	facilitate public consultation
‚Ä¢	coordinate the design of the new structures
‚Ä¢	ensure transparency
‚Ä¢	meet clear milestones and timelines
‚Ä¢	prepare the administrative foundations for the new system
Crucially, no member of the interim body may serve in the new government. This prevents self interest, power consolidation, or manipulation of the transition.
The interim body must also remain fully accountable to the people. If citizens lose confidence in any interim member, they must have the power to replace that person immediately. This ensures that the transition remains aligned with public will and prevents the emergence of a new political class.
In this way, the transformation becomes:
‚Ä¢	voluntary
‚Ä¢	citizen driven
‚Ä¢	transparent
‚Ä¢	time bounded
‚Ä¢	protected from power seeking
‚Ä¢	tailored to each nation‚Äôs identity
It is an evolution guided by the people, not a revolution imposed from above.

