‚≠ê Key Principle: Competence Based Participation Model
The governance system must be built on a competence based participation model, ensuring that decision making authority grows in proportion to demonstrated responsibility, experience, and community trust. Every citizen begins by participating in decisions within their immediate environment ‚Äî their neighbourhood or local community ‚Äî where they understand the issues directly and can see the consequences of their choices.
Through the 1 in 10 representation structure, individuals who earn the confidence of their peers rise to higher levels of responsibility. At each layer, representatives must consult those below them, ensuring that higher level decisions remain grounded in real community needs. Only those who have proven competence, integrity, and accountability at lower levels may participate in regional or national decision making.
This prevents impulsive mass decisions, protects the legal and financial systems from destabilising demands, and ensures that authority is always exercised by those who have earned it through service, not by popularity, emotion, or opportunism. It is a system where responsibility is earned, not assumed, and where the people‚Äôs will is expressed through a structured, stable, bottom up process.

